Task status: BLOCKED — root cause + partial fix in place, but unable to fully verify visually before hitting the tool-call cap.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════
WHAT NOFI ASKED
═══════════════════════════════════════════════
"check the Memory graph if working properly as i dont see new memories being bright shining star"

═══════════════════════════════════════════════
ROOT CAUSE FOUND
═══════════════════════════════════════════════
The "shining star" rendering code IS working correctly — when the camera is positioned at the latest node, the golden star + halo IS visible (confirmed by browser_vision screenshot — saw the orange/gold star cluster after manually flying the camera to it).

The real bug is the AUTO-FLY-CAMERA-TO-STAR path failing silently:

1. On page load, `flyCameraToNode()` in `code/memory-graph.html` polls node.x/y/z in a rAF loop with MAX_ATTEMPTS=30 (~500ms).
2. With 1772 nodes starting at (0,0,0), the d3 simulation needs >500ms to scatter them and assign positions. The rAF chain gives up BEFORE positions are assigned.
3. The camera never flies to the latest node. The latest node ends up ~1100+ units away from the default camera position, so the star is rendered but off-screen / imperceptibly small.
4. The dev's workaround was the "⭐ Latest ⭐" banner click (line 1033, `wireShineBanner`) that manually flies to the star. NOFI doesn't know about it.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════
FIX APPLIED (committed to file, NOT yet committed to git)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════
File: /home/nofidofi/NofiTech-Ind/01_projects/mission-control/code/memory-graph.html

Two changes inside `flyCameraToNode()` + `setShiningNode()`:

A. `MAX_ATTEMPTS` 30 → 180 (~3s, enough for the simulation to assign positions to 1700+ nodes)
B. Added a 3500ms `setTimeout` safety net that forces a fly-to regardless of rAF chain state (handles throttled tabs, rAF-chain-killed scenarios)
C. `setShiningNode` now also calls `Graph.d3ReheatSimulation()` so the newest node gets an x/y/z assigned quickly when the star changes.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════
VERIFICATION
═══════════════════════════════════════════════
- Browser confirmed new code IS loaded (new comment, new MAX_ATTEMPTS=180, new safety-net timer all present in DOM)
- Manual `Graph.cameraPosition(starPos, starLookAt, 500)` from console DID fly the camera and reveal the golden star (visual proof in screenshot)
- Initial-load auto-fly path was NOT visually verified before the tool-call cap — couldn't reload page and observe final state

═══════════════════════════════════════════════
DISCOVERY (won't be acted on now)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════
3d-force-graph v1.77.0 has a cameraPosition API quirk: the 4-arg `cameraPosition(pos, center, duration, transitionMs)` form treats args differently than the documented signature. Calling with the 3-arg form works but the lookAt animation can be interrupted by OrbitControls re-orienting. The existing code already handles this via `ctrls.target.set(node.x, node.y, node.z)` after cameraPosition, which is correct.

